Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist1:Thought: My motivation stems from a critical gap in current implicit discourse relation (IDR) classification systems: their brittleness when faced with domain shifts, ambiguous context, or subtle linguistic variations. While transfer learning and attention mechanisms have improved performance, they often fail to dynamically recalibrate the model’s focus when initial predictions are uncertain—a common issue in discourse parsing where surface cues are sparse. Inspired by Papers 1–3, I observed that effective communication hinges on *adaptive re-interpretation*: reframing messages for receptiveness (Paper 1), rewriting utterances reflectively (Paper 2), and simulating listener understanding (Paper 3). These works emphasize real-time feedback loops and perspective-taking in language generation. However, such self-correcting dynamics are underexplored in *discourse understanding*, especially in classification tasks. Most IDR models operate in a feedforward manner, lacking mechanisms to "rethink" their initial anchoring of discourse units. My idea introduces **Self-Correcting Discourse Understanding**, where a classifier doesn’t just predict once but iteratively refines its interpretation via *adaptive re-anchoring*—a process guided by uncertainty signals, enriched through transfer learning from related tasks (e.g., coherence modeling, argument strength), and steered by interactive attention that simulates alternative contextual interpretations. This differs fundamentally from static fine-tuning or multi-task learning; instead, it embeds a meta-cognitive loop akin to human revisiting of ambiguous text. The novelty lies in combining *uncertainty-aware re-anchoring* with *interactive simulation* of discourse context, enabling the model to ask: “If my first interpretation were wrong, what other alignments make sense?” This creates a robust, self-diagnosing framework that mimics how humans reread and reinterpret complex texts.

